NNAAMMEE
       huntd - hunt daemon, back-end for hunt game

SSYYNNOOPPSSIISS
       //uussrr//ggaammeess//lliibb//hhuunnttdd [ --ss ] [ --pp port ]

DDEESSCCRRIIPPTTIIOONN
       _h_u_n_t_d  controls  the  multi-player  _h_u_n_t(6) game.  When it
       starts up, it tries to notify all  members  of  the  _h_u_n_t_-
       _p_l_a_y_e_r_s mailing list (see _s_e_n_d_m_a_i_l(8)) by faking a _t_a_l_k(1)
       request from user ``Hunt Game''.

       The --ss option is for running _h_u_n_t_d forever (server  mode).
       This  is  similar to running it under the control of _i_n_e_t_d
       (see below), but it consumes a process table entry when no
       one is playing.

       The  --pp  option  changes  the udp port number used to ren-
       dezvous with the player process and thus allows  for  pri-
       vate  games  of hunt.  This option turns off the notifica-
       tion of players on the _h_u_n_t_-_p_l_a_y_e_r_s mailing list.

IINNEETTDD
       To run _h_u_n_t_d from _i_n_e_t_d, you'll need to put the _h_u_n_t  ser-
       vice in //eettcc//sseerrvviicceess:

              hunt 26740/udp      # multi-player/multi-host maze-
              wars

       and add a line in //eettcc//iinneettdd..ccoonnff:

              hunt dgram  udp  wait  nobody  /usr/games/lib/huntd
              HUNT

       except for Suns which use //eettcc//sseerrvveerrss:

              hunt udp /usr/games/lib/huntd

       Do  not use any of the command line options -- if you want
       _i_n_e_t_d to start up _h_u_n_t_d on a private port, change the port
       listed in //eettcc//sseerrvviicceess.

NNEETTWWOORRKK RREENNDDEEZZVVOOUUSS
       When  _h_u_n_t(6)  starts  up, it broadcasts on the local area
       net (using the broadcast address for  each  interface)  to
       find  a  _h_u_n_t  game  in  progress.   If  a _h_u_n_t_d hears the
       request, it sends back the port number for the  _h_u_n_t  pro-
       cess to connect to.  Otherwise, the _h_u_n_t process starts up
       a _h_u_n_t_d on the local machine and trys to  rendezvous  with
       it.




